# Climbing off the Tiger

In the 20th century, after the disasters of the world wars, and apparent destruction of European
civilization, Julius Evola, a traditionalist philosopher beloved by the far-right, wrote a book
called, "Ride the Tiger: A Survival Manual for the Aristocrats of the Soul." The idea of "riding the
tiger" was a metaphor for how people should navigate a global order defined by liberal capitalism
and communism, powerful global ideologies that Evola viewed as chaotic and misguided, yet,
ultimately, fleeting.

Evola wrote:

> **"The modern world is like a wild beast. He who rides the tiger cannot afford to fall off. He
